    "# NOTES:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Statistical Summary:**\n",
    "\n",
    "    - **General Details:**\n",
    "    \n",
    "    - Based on the count value, we can say that there exists 768 columns i.e. 768 patient records. The data contains no duplicate rows and null values.\n",
    " \n",
    "    - However, we can see that dataset is not free of missing data. Certain physiological measurements cannot physically be zero for a living person.\n",
    " \n",
    "    - When we look at the min value for Glucose which is 0. Same has been observed with BloodPressure, SkinThickness, Insulin and BMI, i.e. all show minimum value = 0.\n",
    " \n",
    "    - For Insulin and SkinThickness, even the 25% quartile is 0. Such values indicates that the massive portion of the data for these columns wasn't recorded, and hence zeros were added. These values are later handled in Data processing by replacing them with NaN(Not A Number) and then imputed using median before training the model.\n",
    "\n",
    "    - **Outliers and Data Skewness:**\n",
    " \n",
    "    - Potential outliers and skewness can be detected by comparing the mean to 50%(Median) and by looking at the gap between the 75% and the max.\n",
    " \n",
    "    - **Pregnancies:** the mean is 3.845 but the maximum is 17. These higher numbers indicate that these might be outliers even though biologically this is possible.\n",
    " \n",
    "    - **Insulin:** this feature is heavily skewed, the median is 30.5 but the mean is all the way up to 79.8. Futhermore, the 75% quartile is 127.25 but the maximum is huge 846. This indicates extreme high-end outliers/\n",
    " \n",
    "    - **DiabetesPedigreeFunction:** Similar to Insulin, the gap between 75% quartile is 0.626 and the max is 2.42, this suggests the presence of upper-bound outliers.\n",
    " \n",
    "    - **Age:** the data is right skewed. The minimum age is 21 and the max is 81 but the median is 29 and mean is 33.2. The mean is higher than the median, i.e. data is pulled up by the older patients.\n",
    " \n",
    "    - The outliers can be verified by using box plot. (Done below)\n",
    " \n",
    "    - **Outcome:** Since it's the target variable, the mean tells the exact proportions of 1s in the dataset. Mean of 0.3489 suggests that approxi. 34.9% of the patients in the dataset are diabetes while the rest 65.1% do not.\n",
    " \n",
    "\n",
    "      \n",
    "-  **Visualization Summary:**\n",
    "    - **Histogram:**\n",
    "    - The histograms is the isolated, tall bars sitting exactly at the 0 mark on the x-axis for Glucose, BloodPressure, SkinThickness, Insulin, and BMI.\n",
    "    - Because clinical measurements like Blood Pressure or BMI cannot realistically be zero, these massive spikes visually confirm that a significant amount of missing data was recorded as 0.\n",
    "    - Especially in Insulin and SkinThickness, where the 0 bin is the highest peak in the entire graph.\n",
    "    - **Skewness Distribution:** Pregnancies and Insulin (even if we ignore the zeros) are heavily right-skewed(Positive Skew). Many of the patients fall into the lower ranges, with a long \"tail\" stretching out to the right for higher values. This visualizes why the mean was so much higher than the median in the descriptive statistics.\n",
    "    - If we ignore the unnatural spikes at zero, features like BloodPressure, BMI, and Glucose display a roughly symmetric, bell-shaped curve.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "    - **Box Plot:**\n",
    "    - Insulin stands out with extreme high-end outliers stretching past 800. DiabetesPedigreeFunction and Age also show significant upper-bound outliers.\n",
    "    - Features like BloodPressure and Glucose (ignoring the zeros) have relatively symmetric boxes, indicating a somewhat normal distribution. In contrast, Pregnancies and Age are tightly packed on the left with long right whiskers, indicating right-skewed data.\n",
    "\n",
    "      \n",
    "    - **Pair Plot:**\n",
    "    - In scatter plot, there is no single pair of features where we can draw a clean, straight line to perfectly separate the two colors. There is significant overlap in almost all combinations.\n",
    "    - Since hue='Outcome' is used with pair plots we can distinguish between patients with diabetes (1) and those without (0).\n",
    "    - Diagonally, there is Kernel Density Estimate (KDE) plots used. KDE plots for Glucose show the clearest separation.\n",
    "    - Features like BloodPressure and SkinThickness have nearly perfectly overlapping distributions for both classes, indicating they are poor standalone predictors for diabetes onset.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "    - **Correlation Heatmap:**\n",
    "    - Values range from -1 to +1\n",
    "    - +1 - Strong positive relationship\n",
    "    - -1 - Strong negative relationship\n",
    "    - 0 - No relationship\n",
    "    - Based on the Outcome row/column, we can see that:\n",
    "    - Glucose - 0.47 has moderate positive score i.e. higher the glucose levels increase diabetes risk. Most influential feature among all features.\n",
    "    - BMI - 0.29 has weak-moderate positive score i.e. higher BMI contributes to diabetes probability\n",
    "    - Age - 0.24 has mild influence i.e. older individuals have slightly higher risk. Same goes Pregnancies-0.22 more pregnencies slightly increase risk\n",
    "    - Features like BloodPressure(0.065), SkinThickness(0.075), Insulin(0.13), DiabetesPedigreeFunction(0.17) have less predicitive control individually\n",
    "    - Most variables show weak correlations, indicating that diabetes prediction depends on a combination of factors rather than a single variable"
   ]
  },
