   "source": [
    "# Model Evaluation\n",
    "# Confusion Matrix - additional score \n",
    "# from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix\n",
    "# cm = confusion_matrix(Y_test, Y_pred)\n",
    "# print(\"Confusion Matrix:\", cm)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Accuracy Score - gives overall correctness\n",
    "print(\"Accuracy Score:\", accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Precision Score - gives correct positive predictions done by the model\n",
    "print(\"\\nPrecision Score:\", precision_score(Y_test, Y_pred))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Recall/Sensitivity Score - captures all actual positives\n",
    "print(\"\\nRecall/Sensitivity Score:\", recall_score(Y_test, Y_pred))\n",
    "\n",
    "# F1 Score  - Balance of precision and recall\n",
    "print(\"\\nF1 Score:\", f1_score(Y_test, Y_pred))\n",
    "\n",
    "# ROC-AUC Score (Area under the curve) - Model's Discrimination Ability\n",
    "print(\"\\nROC-AUC Score:\", roc_auc_score(Y_test, Y_prob)) # requires Y_test and Y_prob as input and not Y_pred\n",
    "\n",
    "# Visualize the ROC Curve\n",
    "tpr, fpr, dummy = roc_curve(Y_test, Y_prob)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.scatter(fpr,tpr)\n",
    "plt.plot(fpr,tpr, color = 'red')\n",
    "plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')# x axis range is 0 to 1, y axis range is 0 to 1, k-- is a line type - dotted\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"False Positive Rate\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"True Positive Rate\")\n",
    "plt.title(\"ROC Curve\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a68801cf-a0fc-4495-bd65-10a3ba101548",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Model Evaluation:\n",
    "- Logistic regression was applied to predict diabetes outcomes based on patient health parameters.\n",
    "- The model was evaluated using multiple metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, and ROC-AUC.\n",
    "- **Accuracy (0.812 or 81.2%):** The model correctly predicted the outcome (whether a patient has diabetes or not) for about 81.2% of the cases in the test set.\n",
    "- **Precision (0.775 or 77.5%):** Out of all the patients the model predicted as having diabetes, 77.5% actually had the disease. This means the model has a relatively low rate of False Positives (telling someone they have diabetes when they don't).\n",
    "- **Recall / Sensitivity (0.608 or 60.8%):** Out of all the patients who actually have diabetes, the model successfully identified 60.8% of them. This means the model missed about 39% of the diabetic patients (False Negatives). This suggests that while the model is cautious and highly precise when predicting diabetes, it struggles to capture all positive cases, missing a portion of actual diabetic patients.\n",
    "- **F1 Score (0.681 or 68.1%):** This represents the harmonic mean of Precision and Recall. The score of 68.1% reflects a reasonable balance, though it is pulled down slightly by the lower Recall score.\n",
    "- **ROC-AUC Score (0.809 or 80.9%):** The Area Under the Curve (AUC) is nearly 81%. This means there is an 80.9% chance that the model will be able to correctly distinguish between a randomly chosen patient with diabetes and a randomly chosen patient without it. The model's AUC in the range of 0.80-0.90 suggesting that this is a good model. If it's above 0.90, it's an excellent model. \n",
    "- **ROC curve:** demonstrated the model’s ability to distinguish between classes.\n",
    "- hile observing the plotted curve, the red line arches well above the black dashed diagonal line. The curve pushes towards the top-left corner (high True Positive Rate, low False Positive Rate), visually confirming the model's strong discriminatory power."
   ]
  },
