  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5057a65a-4538-4937-a195-2d63d4d912de",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Conclusions:\n",
    "- Features such as Glucose and BMI show positive coefficients, indicating that higher values increase the likelihood of diabetes.\n",
    "- Features with negative coefficients reduce the probability of the patient having diabetes.\n",
    "- The magnitude of coefficients reflects the strength of influence.\n",
    "- Feature coefficients provided insights into the impact of variables on prediction. Overall, the model shows reasonable predictive performance.\n",
    "- The current model is actually predicting diabetes probability (where $1$ = Diabetes, $0$ = No Diabetes).\n",
    "- **Increasing Diabetes Risk Predictors(Strong Positive):**\n",
    "    - DiabetesPedigreeFunction ($1.3157$): This is by far the strongest feature in the model. A higher pedigree function score (which represents genetic history and family risk of diabetes) drastically increases the predicted probability of a positive diabetes outcome.\n",
    "    - Pregnancies ($0.1243$) & BMI ($0.0877$): Both of these are moderate positive predictors. As the number of pregnancies or the patient's Body Mass Index increases, the likelihood of developing diabetes also increases.\n",
    "    - Glucose ($0.0391$) & Age ($0.0116$): These also have a positive relationship with diabetes onset.\n",
    "- **Decreasing Diabetes Risk Predictors(Negative Predictors):**\n",
    "    - SkinThickness ($-0.0137$), BloodPressure ($-0.0241$), & Insulin ($-0.0525$): The model assigned negative coefficients to these features, suggesting that higher values in these categories slightly reduce the probability of the patient having diabetes in this model.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "- **The model heavily relies on a patient's genetic history (DiabetesPedigreeFunction), Pregnancies, and BMI to push the prediction toward a positive diabetes diagnosis**"
   ]
